This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with the detection of pulmonary nodules using low-dose CT scans, which is a common application of computer vision techniques. Additionally, the paper proposes an end-to-end framework for nodule detection using deep learning, which is a popular approach in the field of computer vision.

The paper also involves machine learning techniques, specifically deep convolutional neural nets, which suggests that it could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.

The use of deep learning algorithms for nodule detection also suggests that the paper could belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category.

The paper involves the use of medical imaging, which could suggest that it belongs to the Medical Imaging (cs.MS) sub-category.

Finally, the paper could also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category as it deals with the analysis of medical images, which are a form of multimedia data.
